              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Wikipedia states Euler's identity as\ne^{iπ} + 1 = 0,\nwhere e is the base of natural logarithms, i is the imaginary unit (i^2 = −1), and π is the circle constant. It presents this as the special case x = π of Euler’s formula e^{ix} = cos x + i sin x; plugging in x = π gives e^{iπ} = cos π + i sin π = −1, hence e^{iπ} + 1 = 0. Wikipedia also emphasizes that the identity links five fundamental constants (0, 1, e, i, π), uses three basic operations (addition, multiplication, exponentiation), and is widely regarded as an exemplar of mathematical beauty.",
